The march, from Keizersgracht Street to Parliament, was organised by the
Government Communications and Information System (GCIS) as part of the Nelson Mandela and Albertina Sisulu centenary celebrations. GCIS director Geraldine Thopps said the government organisation, in partnership with local government and the City of Cape Town, would undertake further initiatives to help curb violence against women and children. “We are going to go to all the hot spots where violence is rife  so that we can tell communities that this has to stop,” she said. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Mayoral committee member for safety and security JP Smith was at the march. “We have a high number of women and children being abused in our country. This (march) is men saying that they want to be part of the solution,” Smith said. He said the City had a wide range of workshops planned to educate men about abuse. A number of organisations and activists, including  Lucinda Evans from Lavender Hill, were also in attendance. “I am here to support our men who are here to stop the scourge of violence in our country, and I hope this will prompt men to speak to other men and teach them (about the correct way to treat women and children),” Evans said. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
